{
  "answer": "**\"Eardstapa\"** (earth-stepper) appears in *The Wanderer* (lines 5b–6a of the original Old English), in the introductory stanza that precedes the speaker's monologue.[^1][^2] The full context reads:\n\n> Oft him anhaga are gebideð [...]  \n> wadan wræclastas. Wyrd bið ful ared!  \n> **Swa cwæð eardstapa**, earfeþa gemyndig,[^1]\n\n> Often the lone-dweller awaits [...]  \n> tread paths of exile. Wyrd is wholly steadfast!  \n> **So spoke the earth-stepper**, mindful of hardships,[^3]\n\nThis tags the upcoming speaker (the \"lone-dweller\" or *anhaga* of lines 1–5a, rowing across the frozen sea in exile). The modern English title *The Wanderer* renders the poem's theme but flattens this precise kenning.[^4]\n\n**What \"eardstapa\" buys that \"wanderer\" cannot**: Old English compounds pack layered etymology into a single, evocative word, absent in Modern English. *Eard* means \"earth, land, native place, home(land),\" from dwelling (*eardian*, to inhabit) and the world's substance.[^1] *Stapa* is \"stepper, treader,\" from *steppan* (to step).[^2] Thus, *eardstapa* is no airy rover but a heavy-footed tramper of the very soil he has lost—his homeland now alien underfoot amid *wræclastas* (exile-tracks). It fuses physical toil (treading rime-cold earth/sea paths) with spiritual desolation: the wanderer is earth-bound, Wyrd-stamped, his steps echoing lost halls and kin on a decaying *middangeard* (middle-earth).[^3]\n\n\"Wanderer\" suggests vague, rootless drifting (*wander* from OHG *windan*, to turn/wend), losing the compound's grounded pathos: the exilic body's rhythmic, mournful contact with a world of \"wind-blown walls\" and loaned joys.[^3] The kenning names the speaker as earth-stamped survivor, his gait a metric of grief *Wyrd* enforces.[^1]",
